Agreed,  in most case of Singletons, they are created, not because there
&#39;has to be no more than one&#39;, but because the static (aka global) access
method makes it &#39;easier&#39; and &#39;cleaner&#39; to use through out the code base.
These &#39;benefits&#39; are often misguided and can be better solved using the
&#39;just create one&#39; approach

Andrew

On 7/30/07, Nat Pryce &lt;nat.pryce@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt;   The simplest approach I&#39;ve found is that if there is need for only one
&gt; instance of some class in a system, to just create only one instance of
&gt; that
&gt; type.
&gt;
&gt; Adding extra code just to stop me creating more than one is always, in my
&gt; experience, counter-productive. It&#39;s more code to write, test and maintain
&gt; and it gets in the way when I do need to create more than one. For
&gt; example,
&gt; in unit tests. Or when requirements change.
&gt;
&gt; --Nat
